             was indicted for a <rs id="t18310908-255-off1309" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-off1309" type="offenceCategory" value="miscellaneous"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-off1309" type="offenceSubcategory" value="other"></interp>
               misdemeanor
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
               
                  <persName id="t18310908-255-victim1858" type="victimName">
                     JOHN WALTER 
                     CROPLEY
                  <interp inst="t18310908-255-victim1858" type="surname" value="CROPLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-victim1858" type="given" value="JOHN WALTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-victim1858" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-255-off1309 t18310908-255-victim1858"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            . I live in Wilmington-square. On the 1st of September, about a quarter-past nine o'clock, I sold seven loads of straw for 
               <persName id="t18310908-255-person1859">
                  James 
                  Jaggers
               <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1859" type="surname" value="Jaggers"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1859" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1859" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , (of Broxbourne,) in Smithfield market, to Norris, of Chenies-mews, Russell-square; before ten o'clock the same morning, the prisoner, who was a stranger, came to me at the Coach and Horses, Bartholomew-close; he had a frock on - he met me in the passage, and asked if I was Jaggers' salesman; I said Yes - he said he had called for the money for the straw I had sold for Jaggers; he produced a note, which I have; I said, "My name is not Brocklin;" he said, "If you are Jaggers' salesman, that note is for you;" I said I should not pay for the straw till it was delivered, and if Mr. Jaggers would call after it was delivered, it should be paid; I gave him the note back - he returned about half-past twelve o'clock, for the money, and I said the man had not returned from the delivery, meaning the farmer's man, who had to deliver the straw - he said the man would not return, for he had gone home Whitechapel way; I said I was certain he would, for he had not had his spending money - he left, and came again about half-past five o'clock, and from information I had received, I asked him into the house, and said, "Give me the note;" he did so: I opened it, and said, "Who gave you this note?" he said Mr. Jaggers, that he got it at Broxbourn last night, and he had told him to receive the money: I asked if he was related to Jaggers - he said he had married his wife's sister, and lived within a few yards of him; I said I suspected he was a bad fellow, and that Jaggers did not give it to him - he said he did, and it was perfectly right; I sent for an officer, and gave him in charge - the straw came to ten guineas - (note read.)</p>
               <p>London, August 31, 1831.</p>
               <p>MR. BROCKLIN, - Please to deliver to the bearer of this note, the money for the seven loads of straw you have sold, belonging to 
               <persName id="t18310908-255-person1860">
                  James 
                  Jaggers
               <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1860" type="surname" value="Jaggers"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1860" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1860" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , Broxbourne, Hertfordshire.</p>
               <p>Richard Horn; bearer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-255-person1861">
                  JAMES 
                  JAGGERS
               <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1861" type="surname" value="JAGGERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1861" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1861" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a farmer, and live at Broxbourne. I employ the prisoner a little - he married my wife's sister; I sent seven loads of straw to be sold by Cropley - the prisoner did not go with it; I discharged him twelve days before, and never gave him a note to the salesman, or authorised ahy body to receive it - this note is not in my hand-writing.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-255-person1862">
                  FRANCIS 
                  DANNER
               <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1862" type="surname" value="DANNER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1862" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1862" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a plumber. I was at the Coach and Horses about half-past five o'clock, and saw the prisoner demand the money from Cropley for seven loads of straw sold for Jaggers; I saw him produce the note - he said he received it from Jaggers on the previous evening.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-255-person1863">
                  JOHN 
                  PALMER
               <interp inst="t18310908-255-person1863" type="surname" value="PALMER"></interp>
